    "analysis": "We evaluated the top-50 (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs by anomaly counts in the incident window and computed severity metrics. Results show many pairs are constant (global_P95 == global_P5 == in-window values) producing many false-positive anomaly flags with zero severity. Notably, a few pairs show non-zero severity and therefore are better candidates: os_020 - Disk_io_util (high_severity=1.0) and osb_001 - app.succee_rate (low_severity≈0.0655). Most DB MEM_Total and AIOS metrics are constant and have zero severity, so they are unlikely to be the true root cause. OS-level metrics dominate the top anomalies (33 of top-50), while no docker-level KPIs appear in top-50. The earliest anomalies for top candidates appear at the start of the incident window (2020-05-27 00:00:00+08:00).\n\nNext we must focus on the KPI pairs that show meaningful deviation (non-zero severity) to locate the fault occurrence time and component level. We should narrow to all candidate pairs with non-zero severity and inspect their earliest anomaly timestamps to pick the earliest credible fault. This will let us then query traces for interactions involving those components during/just before the earliest anomaly time to identify propagation and the most downstream faulty component if needed.",
